<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-9-2">
  <title>Resources for 9/2</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Given two related quantities and appropriate information about the relationship between the quantities, describe how one quantity changes when the other changes.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Draw a rough graph of the relationship between two given variables.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-related-quantities">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Related Quantities</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>related quantities</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="W8LaY-hDkyU" />

    <problem>
      <title>Related Quantities</title>
      <p>
        For each of the first three problems below, we have a container that is being filled with water.  For each problem, answer the following questions, and explain your answers.
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            What are some quantities that are changing, and what are some quantities that are not changing?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            What does a graph look like when the horizontal axis is time and the vertical axis is volume of water?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            What does a graph look like when the horizontal axis is time and the vertical axis is the height of the water?
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              The container is the shape of a cylinder, and the water is being pumped in at a rate of 2 ft<m>^3</m> per minute.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The container is the shape of an inverted cone (i.e. pointy part down), and the water is being pumped in at a rate of 3 ft<m>^3</m> per minute.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The container is the shape of a hemisphere with the wide part on the bottom (i.e. a dome), and the water is being pumped in at a rate of 1.5 ft<m>^3</m> per minute.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              You have a container where the graphs of volume and height are given below.  The horizontal axis is time for each graph.  Make a reasonable guess at the shape of the container.
            </p>
            <sidebyside widths="45% 45%">
              <image>
                <description><p>Volume Graph</p></description>
	              <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="related-graph-volume-prep">
                  <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                    <definition>f(x)=(5/8)*x</definition>
                    <definition>a = 1</definition>
                    <coordinates bbox="(-1,-1,6,6)">                
                      <grid-axes xlabel="t" ylabel="V"/>
                      <graph function="f" domain="(0,6)"/>
                    </coordinates>
                  </diagram>
                </prefigure>
              </image>
              <image>
                <description><p>Height Graph</p></description>
	              <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="related-graph-height-prep">
                  <diagram dimensions="(300, 300)" margins="5">
                    <definition>f(x)=0.25*x^2</definition>
                    <definition>g(x)=3*sin(0.5*(x-3))+2.25</definition>
                    <coordinates bbox="(-1,-1,6,6)">
                      <grid-axes xlabel="t" ylabel="h"/>
                      <graph function="f" domain="(0,3)"/>
                      <graph function="g" domain="(3,6)"/>
                    </coordinates>
                  </diagram>
                </prefigure>
              </image>
            </sidebyside>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Optional Reading</title>
    <p>
      Section 1.1: pp. 1-8
    </p>
    <p>
      Here is a link for the <url href="https://activecalculus.org/prelude/sec-changing-in-tandem.html">HTML version of Section 1.1</url>.
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>